Learn more how customers reviews work on Amazon View Image Gallery Amazon Customer 5.0 out of 5 stars Sounds exactly like a Schoeps......Really. Reviewed in the United States on February 24, 2016 Sounds almost exactly like a Schoeps CMC 6......no, seriously. I'm a seasoned engineer working and living in the Nashville area. I've been engineering for almost 9 years here and have worked on an incredibly diverse range of music genres. I had used the e70s a lot in the past, but finally decided to purchase a pair of my own. I've always known that the e70 was essentially attempting to copy the amplifier circuit of a Schoeps, but finally got to shoot the two of them out today. SCARY similar. Not kidding. With a room of 8 people taking turns doing an AB comparison between the two mics, only one person picked out the mics correctly. To be specific, the chain was: Martin DC1E mic'd at the 12th fret with both mics, capsules side by side 6 to 8 inches away from the instrument. Both mics went into their own API 512 preamp, straight to the multitrack sends (pro tools inputs). I'm telling you there's hardly a nickel's difference between these two mics, and there's definitely not a $1500 difference. I'd buy 10 of these before I bought 1 Schoeps. If you're on the fence, don't be. I've also shot these out with Neumann M150's and 582s on piano with amazing results. A sure diamond in the rough. Buy one......like...yesterday. Read more Helpful Report abuse See all reviews Top reviews from other countries Translate all reviews to English mundini5.0 out of 5 stars Hochprofessionelles Mikrofon zum Superpreis Reviewed in Germany on July 8, 2016Style: Small Diaphragm Cardioid and OmniVerified Purchase Habe vier dieser Mikrofone seit 8 Jahren im Einsatz für Chor- Orchester- und Orgelaufnahmen. Die Qualität ist überwältigend und braucht sich in keiner Weise hinter teueren Schoeps MK21 oder dpa 4006 verstecken. In den CAD E70 ist eine Kopie der Schoeps Verstärkerelektronik verbaut. Der Klang ist nahezu identisch mit Schoeps CMC6 - nur für ca. 1/10 -1/20 tel des Preises. Vor allem die Qualität im low end Bereich ist bemerkenswert. Die Orgelbässe kommen abgrundtief und voll. Wem das zu viel ist, der kann über einen high pass filter eingreifen. Zwar sind die dpa 4006 neutraler und etwas klarer, dafür klingen die CAD e70 etwas wärmer und voller. Das etwas höhere Eigenrauschen ist vernachlässigbar.Im Lieferumfang sind sowohl Omni als auch Cardioidkapseln. Damit stehen einem alle Möglichkeiten offen. Zudem sind Spinne, klassische Mikrohalterung und Windschutz enthalten.Wer ein hochprofessionelles Mikrofon zu einem absurd niedrigen Preis für akustische Instrumente, Chorgesang, Orchester oder v.a. View Image Gallery Amazon Customer 5.0 out of 5 stars Sounds exactly like a Schoeps......Really. Reviewed in the United States on February 24, 2016 Sounds almost exactly like a Schoeps CMC 6......no, seriously. I'm a seasoned engineer working and living in the Nashville area. I've been engineering for almost 9 years here and have worked on an incredibly diverse range of music genres. I had used the e70s a lot in the past, but finally decided to purchase a pair of my own. I've always known that the e70 was essentially attempting to copy the amplifier circuit of a Schoeps, but finally got to shoot the two of them out today. SCARY similar. Not kidding. With a room of 8 people taking turns doing an AB comparison between the two mics, only one person picked out the mics correctly. To be specific, the chain was: Martin DC1E mic'd at the 12th fret with both mics, capsules side by side 6 to 8 inches away from the instrument. Both mics went into their own API 512 preamp, straight to the multitrack sends (pro tools inputs). I'm telling you there's hardly a nickel's difference between these two mics, and there's definitely not a $1500 difference. I'd buy 10 of these before I bought 1 Schoeps. If you're on the fence, don't be. I've also shot these out with Neumann M150's and 582s on piano with amazing results. A sure diamond in the rough. Buy one......like...yesterday.             5.0 out of 5 stars
            
                Sounds exactly like a Schoeps......Really.
            
            
            
                
                    
                        Reviewed in the United States on February 24, 2016
                    
                    
                
            
        
        
            Sounds almost exactly like a Schoeps CMC 6......no, seriously.  I'm a seasoned engineer working and living in the Nashville area.  I've been engineering for almost 9 years here and have worked on an incredibly diverse range of music genres.  I had used the e70s a lot in the past, but finally decided to purchase a pair of my own.  I've always known that the e70 was essentially attempting to copy the amplifier circuit of a Schoeps, but finally got to shoot the two of them out today.  SCARY similar.  Not kidding.  With a room of 8 people taking turns doing an AB comparison between the two mics, only one person picked out the mics correctly.  To be specific, the chain was:  Martin DC1E mic'd at the 12th fret with both mics, capsules side by side 6 to 8 inches away from the instrument.  Both mics went into their own API 512 preamp, straight to the multitrack sends (pro tools inputs).  I'm telling you there's hardly a nickel's difference between these two mics, and there's definitely not a $1500 difference.  I'd buy 10 of these before I bought 1 Schoeps.  If you're on the fence, don't be.  I've also shot these out with Neumann M150's and 582s on piano with amazing results.  A sure diamond in the rough.  Buy one......like...yesterday.

Sounds almost exactly like a Schoeps CMC 6......no, seriously.  I'm a seasoned engineer working and living in the Nashville area.  I've been engineering for almost 9 years here and have worked on an incredibly diverse range of music genres.  I had used the e70s a lot in the past, but finally decided to purchase a pair of my own.  I've always known that the e70 was essentially attempting to copy the amplifier circuit of a Schoeps, but finally got to shoot the two of them out today.  SCARY similar.  Not kidding.  With a room of 8 people taking turns doing an AB comparison between the two mics, only one person picked out the mics correctly.  To be specific, the chain was:  Martin DC1E mic'd at the 12th fret with both mics, capsules side by side 6 to 8 inches away from the instrument.  Both mics went into their own API 512 preamp, straight to the multitrack sends (pro tools inputs).  I'm telling you there's hardly a nickel's difference between these two mics, and there's definitely not a $1500 difference.  I'd buy 10 of these before I bought 1 Schoeps.  If you're on the fence, don't be.  I've also shot these out with Neumann M150's and 582s on piano with amazing results.  A sure diamond in the rough.  Buy one......like...yesterday.

Sounds almost exactly like a Schoeps CMC 6......no, seriously.  I'm a seasoned engineer working and living in the Nashville area.  I've been engineering for almost 9 years here and have worked on an incredibly diverse range of music genres.  I had used the e70s a lot in the past, but finally decided to purchase a pair of my own.  I've always known that the e70 was essentially attempting to copy the amplifier circuit of a Schoeps, but finally got to shoot the two of them out today.  SCARY similar.  Not kidding.  With a room of 8 people taking turns doing an AB comparison between the two mics, only one person picked out the mics correctly.  To be specific, the chain was:  Martin DC1E mic'd at the 12th fret with both mics, capsules side by side 6 to 8 inches away from the instrument.  Both mics went into their own API 512 preamp, straight to the multitrack sends (pro tools inputs).  I'm telling you there's hardly a nickel's difference between these two mics, and there's definitely not a $1500 difference.  I'd buy 10 of these before I bought 1 Schoeps.  If you're on the fence, don't be.  I've also shot these out with Neumann M150's and 582s on piano with amazing results.  A sure diamond in the rough.  Buy one......like...yesterday.

Top reviews from other countries Translate all reviews to English mundini5.0 out of 5 stars Hochprofessionelles Mikrofon zum Superpreis Reviewed in Germany on July 8, 2016Style: Small Diaphragm Cardioid and OmniVerified Purchase Habe vier dieser Mikrofone seit 8 Jahren im Einsatz für Chor- Orchester- und Orgelaufnahmen. Die Qualität ist überwältigend und braucht sich in keiner Weise hinter teueren Schoeps MK21 oder dpa 4006 verstecken. In den CAD E70 ist eine Kopie der Schoeps Verstärkerelektronik verbaut. Der Klang ist nahezu identisch mit Schoeps CMC6 - nur für ca. 1/10 -1/20 tel des Preises. Vor allem die Qualität im low end Bereich ist bemerkenswert. Die Orgelbässe kommen abgrundtief und voll. Wem das zu viel ist, der kann über einen high pass filter eingreifen. Zwar sind die dpa 4006 neutraler und etwas klarer, dafür klingen die CAD e70 etwas wärmer und voller. Das etwas höhere Eigenrauschen ist vernachlässigbar.Im Lieferumfang sind sowohl Omni als auch Cardioidkapseln. Damit stehen einem alle Möglichkeiten offen. Zudem sind Spinne, klassische Mikrohalterung und Windschutz enthalten.Wer ein hochprofessionelles Mikrofon zu einem absurd niedrigen Preis für akustische Instrumente, Chorgesang, Orchester oder v.a.
